    {
        "user": "UC2A2ARPT",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1598508046.095000",
        "edited": {
            "user": "UC2A2ARPT",
            "ts": "1598508154.000000"
        },
        "client_msg_id": "CBF92BA1-3319-4937-BFF8-7DCF77F737E8",
        "text": "The thing I get from this, that I didn't get from A(n) Whole New World (for instance) is that these Rabl layers can be nothing more than a named text style with a visibility toggle. In the video, the style is just a color. The style could be a little fancier — maybe different fonts, why not. But the process of defining a new layer ought to be just like photoshop: add a layer on the fly, name it (or not), put stuff in it. The barrier being so low, you don't even acknowledge how powerful it is.\n\nSure, we could start imagining all the built-in layers a code editor could add, and that's cool... but that's a different thing than a tool just for a writer to define their own conventions around. Like the difference between adjustment layers (PS) or nondestructive filter layers (Pixelmator Pro) and regular layers (every nontrivial image, video, music, etc editor).\n\nI want both, but they're separate ideas.",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
